Here's how to implement all three pieces:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation with a confirmation dialog**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your page:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        // Fire-and-forget since the override is synchronous
        Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
            {
                _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            }
        });

        return true; // cancel the default navigation
    }
}
```

> **Note:** `OnBackButtonPressed` only fires for the **hardware/OS back button** (Android). It does *not* intercept the Shell navigation bar back arrow.

**3. Custom "Cancel" toolbar button replacing the shell back arrow**

Hide the default back button and add your own:

```xml
<ContentPage
    xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
    x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
    Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            x:Key="CancelBackButton"
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Or set it inline:

```xml
<Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                        Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
</Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand CancelCommand { get; }

public EditProductViewModel()
{
    CancelCommand = new Command(async () =>
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!leave) return;
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    });
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the nav-bar back arrow tap — the confirmation logic goes there.
- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the Android hardware back button separately.
- Both paths should share the same "unsaved changes" flag so behavior is consistent.
